{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532336"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:25:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:25:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14668"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14668"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.28,0.2,0.23,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108812"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7361"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14668"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91175"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"619"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17961"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46063"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108812"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of dysuria, frequency, and fever. He reports feeling generally unwell with rigors and lower back pain. His medical history includes prostate cancer treated with partial prostatectomy five years ago, hypertension, and osteoarthritis. His medications include amlodipine and paracetamol. He is concerned his cancer may have returned.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.7\u00b0C. Gentle digital rectal examination reveals a tender, boggy prostate. Blood tests show prostate specific antigen 15.2 \u00b5g/L (0-4.0). Analgesia has been given and urine and blood cultures have been taken and are pending.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Magnetic resonance imaging of the prostate","Oral trimethoprim","Oral ciprofloxacin","Intravenous ampicillin and gentamicin","Prostate ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of acute bacterial prostatitis: fever, dysuria, and a tender prostate on examination. The most common causative organisms are \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E and other gram-negative bacteria. Despite his history of prostate cancer and elevated PSA, the acute presentation strongly suggests infection rather than cancer recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral ciprofloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management as it is the first-line antibiotic for acute bacterial prostatitis according to Australian guidelines. It achieves excellent penetration into prostatic tissue and is effective against the common pathogens involved. Treatment should continue for 14-28 days. The patient should also be advised to increase fluid intake, and a repeat PSA after treatment should show a decreased level if the elevation was due to inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral trimethoprim\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative antibiotic for acute bacterial prostatitis, but it is not the first-line therapy according to current Australian guidelines. While it does achieve good prostatic tissue penetration, ciprofloxacin is preferred for empirical therapy due to its broader spectrum of activity against the likely pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging of the prostate\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in the acute setting. While it may be useful for cancer staging or evaluating complications like prostatic abscess, the current priority is treating the acute infection. Imaging should be deferred until after the acute episode has resolved if still clinically indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstate ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely needed for uncomplicated acute prostatitis. It may be considered if there is concern for prostatic abscess, which would typically present with more severe symptoms, failure to respond to antibiotics, or fluctuance on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ampicillin and gentamicin\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered in a hospital setting for severe cases of prostatitis or if the patient is systemically unwell, which is not the case here. The patient is stable enough for outpatient management with oral antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute bacterial prostatitis presents with dysuria, fever, and a tender prostate on examination.","PSA can be elevated in both prostate cancer and prostatitis, making it unreliable for cancer diagnosis during acute inflammation.","Ciprofloxacin is the first-line antibiotic for acute bacterial prostatitis due to its excellent prostatic tissue penetration."],"references":["Xiong S, Liu X, Deng W, Zhou Z, Li Y, Tu Y, Chen L, Wang G, Fu B. Pharmacological interventions for bacterial prostatitis. Frontiers in pharmacology. 2020 Apr 30;11:504. Available online at ; https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7203426/","Dickson G. Prostatitis: diagnosis and treatment. Australian family physician. 2013 Apr;42(4):216-9. Available online at ; https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/a8d4732f-fcc1-401b-aca2-a24b0297a7c3/Prostatitis.aspx","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Prostatitis. In: eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2025 [cited 2025 Apr 17]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91175"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14668"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91175"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T15:28:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T15:30:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7361"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108812"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"6